        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>self-winding clocks [300201686], clocks by movement [300041606], clocks [300041575], timepieces by form [300196327], timepieces [300041573], measuring devices for extent [300195701], measuring devices (instruments) [300207870], Measuring Devices (hierarchy name) [300207851], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Clocks with a running duration of eight days. They are either longcase or bracket in form. The interval for winding is seven days, but the additional day is to enable a day's delay in winding. They can often be identified by winding squares on the dial.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047099/Smith, Country Life Dictionary of Clocks (1979)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Klokken, in de vorm van staande horloges of consoleklokken, die acht dagen kunnen lopen na het opwinden. Ze moeten om de zeven dagen worden opgewonden, maar de extra dag biedt de mogelijkheid van één dag uitstel. Ze zijn vaak te herkennen aan sleutelgaten op de wijzerplaat.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Uhr mit einer Gangdauer von acht Tagen. Sie gehört entweder zu den Standuhren oder zu den Stutzuhren. Die Zeitspanne bis zum Aufziehen beträgt sieben Tage, aber der zusätzliche Tag ermöglicht eine Verspätung von einem Tag beim Aufziehen. Oft kann sie am quadratischen Loch zum Aufziehen auf dem Ziffernblatt identifiziert werden.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>8天上1次發條的時鐘，外表為長方箱狀或壁鐘狀，上發條的間隔是7天，附加的1天是為了延遲1天上發條的時間；此類時鐘的特色為鐘面的方形發條孔。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
